      <title>We don't really need Mastery aa for tinkering</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Trade&amp;message.id=12159#M12159</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;We don't really need Tinkering Mastery AA&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The way mastery works is that it adds the effect as if you have a higher skill in the tradeskill in question.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;End result: Mastery AA is mostly worthless at the moment for most people- The benefit is temporary till they hit the higher skill which would have provided the same skillup chance as lower skill with mastery aa.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Only a handfull of combines benefit at the moment from mastery aa at 300.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Devs have said they would work on making mastery more usefull by putting items with a higher trivial in game for which the aa will have an impact still.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;So basicly the mastery will eventually be a top-up you need on top of 300 to do some combines with minimum failure chance.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;As long as tinkering recipes are made with the knowledge that there is no AA, there is no real issue/case for the aa except another path to get to &amp;quot;max tinkering skill&amp;quot;  (after aa modification). Seeing the difficulty of implementing racial aa and the issues it would cause for all other races that want something in the way of AA's, the pitfalls seem far bigger than the benefits of the aa.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I rather see development time go into more usefull projects&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;aamlaan wrote:&lt;br&gt;The real issue is it's hard to code AA for race only, they can do class only AA.  Chanty get JC master but not other classes.  What do other classes get in place of missing JC AA?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;div&gt;Enchanters got this way way back. I think it was during POP but don't quote me on that. They got it to fill up the aa point distribution across the classes. Appareently there was little else to give them points for at that time.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;To give other classes the mastery AA, means that they need to get back to the drawing boards to figure out how to implement a suitable &amp;quot;replacement reward&amp;quot; for the enchanters because they would not benefit in their development if only the JC aa was introduced for the other classes. They didn;t get some other (non disclosed) alternative back then when other classes did get aa's to develop themselves. This seems to be a big issue with both developers and enchanters. Enchanters are mixed about handing out the aa to all and if so, how to be &amp;quot;compensated&amp;quot;. Developers seem to have an aversion of even discussing the merits of the case in regards with other tradeskills and balance across the classes. Maybe they just can;t come up with some aa that will satisfy the enchanters without pissing off  the other classes by giving the enchanters something obviously overpowered (like the ranger spell adjustments &amp;lt;sic&amp;gt;)&lt;br&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
